{{GeoGroup}} {{Original research|date=November 2017}} Some locations on free, publicly viewable satellite map services have '''missing, incomplete, or unclear map data'''. In some cases, these regions have been intentionally digitally obscured or blurred.<ref name="Deshpande">{{Cite news|author=Deshpande, Rajeev|title=Google Earth agrees to blur pix of key Indian sites|newspaper=The Times of India|date=4 February 2007|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2007-02-04/india/27872874_1_google-earth-images-concern-that-unrestricted-pictures}}{{cbignore}}</ref> [[Westchester County, New York]], for example, has asked [[Google]] to blur potential terrorism targets (such as an amusement park, a beach, and parking lots) from its [[satellite imagery]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Westchester 'Blurs' Out Terror Targets On Google|url=http://wcbstv.com/technology/google.maps.westchester.2.719388.html|accessdate=15 July 2015|agency=[[WCBS-TV]]|date=8 May 2008|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080510223350/http://wcbstv.com/technology/google.maps.westchester.2.719388.html|archivedate=10 May 2008}}</ref>
In some cases, censorship of certain sites has been removed. When [[Google Maps]] was launched, images of the [[White House]] and [[United States Capitol]] in [[Washington, D.C.]] were blurred out; current versions of Google Maps and [[Google Earth]] show these sites uncensored.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/07/21/AR2007072101296.html|title= Google's View of D.C. Melds New and Sharp, Old and Fuzzy | date= 22 July 2007|publisher= Washington Post | first=Jenna | last=Johnson | accessdate=23 May 2010}}</ref>
==Countries in official contact with Google Maps== During talks with the [[India]]n government, Google issued a statement saying "Google has been talking and will continue to talk to the Indian government about any security concerns it may have regarding Google Earth."<ref name="BBC-2007-02-05">{{Cite news|title=Google Earth prompts Indian fears|date=5 February 2007|newspaper=BBC News |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/6331033.stm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080308184315/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/6331033.stm|archivedate=8 March 2008|deadurl=no}}</ref> Google agreed to blur images on request of the Indian government.<ref name="Deshpande" />
The Australian government has decided that images of sensitive areas are not a risk, due to poor level of detail.<ref>{{cite web|first=Judy|last=Skatssoon |url=http://abc.net.au/science/articles/2005/08/08/1432823.htm |title=Lucas Heights image stays on Google |location=34.0516520;150.9804300 |publisher=[[Australian Broadcasting Corporation|ABC]] |date=8 August 2005 |accessdate=3 July 2013}}</ref> It was reported that in the lead-up to the [[APEC]] forum in [[Sydney]] held in September 2007 certain key locations in images of the city's central business district, where APEC leaders were meeting, might have been intentionally reduced in resolution; however, Google has indicated that the change was unrelated to APEC, while the [[New South Wales|NSW]] police said that they knew nothing about the change in Google's images. It is known that images of Her Majesty's Australian Prisons are intentionally blurred out. Images of the prime minister's official residence, [[The Lodge (Australia)|The Lodge]] have not been blurred. However, images of its roof have been and the entrance to The Lodge is blurred in [[Google Street View]].<ref>{{Cite news| last = Moses| first = Asher| title = Google's photos of Sydney go all fuzzy| newspaper = [[Sydney Morning Herald]]| date = 13 August 2007| url = http://www.smh.com.au/news/web/aerial-images-of-cbd-fuzzed-out-before-apec/2007/08/13/1186857396182.html?page=fullpage#contentSwap1| accessdate = 13 August 2007}}</ref>
The government of [[Malaysia]] has stated that it will not ask Google to censor sensitive areas because [[Streisand effect|that would identify the locations]] it deemed to be sensitive.<ref>[http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/nst/Wednesday/National/20070328080627/Article/local1_html Parliament In Brief: ‘No need to blur images’] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070509182328/http://www.nst.com.my/Current_News/nst/Wednesday/National/20070328080627/Article/local1_html |date=May 9, 2007 }}</ref>
==Examples of map locations with missing or unclear data== <!-- PLEASE do not list every little censored location in every map service. If we did that, the list would be impossible to fully read. Limit this to notable and exceptional cases ONLY; Private homes in particular number in the thousands, so any addition of blurred private homes will be reverted. -->
Most military and defense facilities, along with many private homes, appear blurred in mapping services. The vast majority of [[Antarctica]] is also in low resolution due to the bright, often featureless, ice and snow making high-resolution imaging both difficult and largely unnecessary.
